%S A338288 1,10,3,6,15,2,5,8,11,24,27,48,23,20,39,16,19,22,41,44,71,74,45,42,69,
%T A338288 38,63,66,99,36,61,94,31,54,85,124,51,80,83,120,123,168,81,118,77,114,
%U A338288 73,108,151,68,103,64,67,102,143,146,195,100,141,96,137,60,93,90
%N A338288 Squares visited by the white knight when a white knight and a black knight are moving on a spirally numbered board, always to the lowest available unvisited square; white moves first.
%C A338288 Board is numbered with the square spiral:
%C A338288   17--16--15--14--13   .
%C A338288    |               |   .
%C A338288   18   5---4---3  12   .
%C A338288    |   |       |   |   .
%C A338288   19   6   1---2  11   .
%C A338288    |   |           |   .
%C A338288   20   7---8---9--10   .
%C A338288    |                   .
%C A338288   21--22--23--24--25--26
%C A338288 Both knights start on square 1, white moves to the lowest unvisited square (10), black then moves to the lowest unvisited square (12) and so on...
%C A338288 This sequence is finite, on the white knight's 3999th step, square 3606 is visited, after which there are no unvisited squares within one knight move.
%C A338288 The sequences generated by 4 knights and 8 knights also produce new sequences not yet in the OEIS.
%C A338288 Note that the black knight is trapped after the 1879th step when it visits square 4242; the sequence gives all the squares visited by the white knight up to and beyond that step until it is also trapped. - _Scott R. Shannon_, Apr 27 2026
%H A338288 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A338288/b338288.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..4000</a>
%H A338288 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A338288/a338288_1.png">Image of the white knight's path</a>. The final square is shown in red while the 8 visited squares around the final square are highlighted in dark blue.
%H A338288 N. J. A. Sloane and Brady Haran, <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RGQe8waGJ4w">The Trapped Knight</a>, Numberphile video (2019).
